if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['oph_p2_ocular_patho']=[
  {q:"A 3-year-old child presents with leukocoria and strabismus. CT scan demonstrates intraocular calcification. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Congenital cataract","Retinoblastoma","Persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous","Coats disease","Toxocariasis"],a:1,e:"Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy of childhood and classically presents with leukocoria and strabismus. Intraocular calcification on imaging is highly characteristic.<br><br>The tumor arises from primitive retinal cells due to RB1 gene mutation and may be hereditary or sporadic. Early diagnosis is critical for survival and globe preservation.<br><br>Congenital cataract (A) causes leukocoria but does not typically produce calcification. Coats disease (D) may mimic retinoblastoma but usually lacks calcified intraocular masses.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinoblastoma is most likely to inherit mutation involving which gene?",o:["P53","APC","RB1","BRCA1","WT1"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma results from mutation of the RB1 tumor suppressor gene located on chromosome 13q14. Bilateral disease strongly suggests hereditary mutation.<br><br>Hereditary retinoblastoma increases risk of secondary malignancies such as osteosarcoma later in life. Genetic counseling is therefore important.<br><br>P53 mutation (A) is associated with Li-Fraumeni syndrome, while WT1 (E) is linked to Wilms tumor.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A slowly enlarging pearly eyelid lesion with telangiectasia and central ulceration near the medial canthus is most likely:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Melanoma","Keratoacanthoma"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is the commonest malignant eyelid tumor and classically appears as a pearly nodular lesion with rolled edges and telangiectasia.<br><br>The medial canthus is particularly important because tumors here may invade the orbit early. Metastasis is uncommon but local destruction may be severe.<br><br>Sebaceous carcinoma (C) often mimics recurrent chalazion, whereas squamous carcinoma (B) tends to appear more ulcerative and keratinized.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"An elderly woman develops recurrent unilateral \"chalazion\" with loss of eyelashes and diffuse lid thickening. Which diagnosis should be suspected?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Molluscum contagiosum","Papilloma","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is a highly malignant eyelid tumor often arising from meibomian glands. It commonly masquerades as recurrent chalazion or chronic blepharoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Loss of eyelashes, diffuse lid thickening, and recurrent unilateral disease are important warning signs. Early biopsy is essential because delay worsens prognosis.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) usually appears as pearly nodular lesions. Dermoid cysts (E) are congenital benign masses rather than destructive recurrent lid lesions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with choroidal melanoma most commonly presents with:",o:["Painless progressive visual symptoms","Leukocoria","Painful red eye only","Complete blindness overnight","Severe proptosis initially"],a:0,e:"Choroidal melanoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy in adults and often presents with blurred vision, photopsia, or visual field defects.<br><br>Fundoscopy may reveal pigmented dome-shaped choroidal masses with associated subretinal fluid. Ultrasonography commonly demonstrates acoustic hollowness.<br><br>Leukocoria (B) is more characteristic of retinoblastoma. Sudden complete blindness (D) is unusual as an initial presentation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with hereditary retinoblastoma is at increased risk of developing which secondary malignancy later in life?",o:["Osteosarcoma","Thyroid carcinoma","Renal cell carcinoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Pancreatic carcinoma"],a:0,e:"Patients with hereditary RB1 mutation have increased susceptibility to secondary non-ocular malignancies, especially osteosarcoma. Radiation therapy further increases this risk.<br><br>Long-term follow-up and genetic counseling are therefore crucial in hereditary retinoblastoma survivors.<br><br>Thyroid carcinoma (B) and pancreatic carcinoma (E) are not classically associated with RB1 mutation syndromes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A pigmented conjunctival lesion with feeder vessels and progressive enlargement is most concerning for:",o:["Pinguecula","Conjunctival nevus","Conjunctival melanoma","Pterygium","Dermolipoma"],a:2,e:"Conjunctival melanoma often arises from primary acquired melanosis and demonstrates growth, feeder vessels, irregular pigmentation, and nodularity.<br><br>These lesions carry metastatic potential and require prompt excision with appropriate margins and histopathological evaluation.<br><br>Pinguecula (A) and pterygium (D) are benign degenerative lesions lacking malignant melanocytic features.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with orbital rhabdomyosarcoma most likely presents with:",o:["Slowly progressive painless ptosis","Rapid unilateral proptosis in child","Bilateral leukocoria","Chronic blepharitis","Episcleritis"],a:1,e:"Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common primary orbital malignancy of childhood and typically causes rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis.<br><br>The tumor may mimic orbital cellulitis clinically. Imaging and urgent biopsy are essential because early chemoradiotherapy improves survival.<br><br>Leukocoria (C) suggests retinoblastoma rather than orbital malignancy. Chronic blepharitis (D) is unrelated to orbital tumors.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic breast carcinoma develops choroidal metastasis. Which symptom is most likely?",o:["Progressive blurred vision","Sudden painful blindness","Severe photophobia only","Congenital nystagmus","Acute angle closure"],a:0,e:"The choroid is the most common site of ocular metastasis because of its rich vascular supply. Breast carcinoma is a major primary source in women.<br><br>Patients typically develop blurred vision, metamorphopsia, or visual field defects due to serous retinal detachment overlying metastatic lesions.<br><br>Acute angle closure (E) is not the typical manifestation of choroidal metastasis. Congenital nystagmus (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with basal cell carcinoma of the lower eyelid most commonly develops local invasion toward the:",o:["Orbit","Retina","Optic chiasm","Choroid","Lacrimal gland only"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma rarely metastasizes but can cause extensive local tissue destruction and orbital invasion if neglected.<br><br>Medial canthal tumors are particularly dangerous because tissue planes allow early orbital extension. Complete excision is therefore essential.<br><br>Retinal or choroidal invasion (A, D) is not the usual direct spread pattern of eyelid tumors.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with unilateral leukocoria. Which condition among the following is considered the most life-threatening differential diagnosis?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Congenital cataract","Persistent pupillary membrane","Retinal coloboma","Albinism"],a:0,e:"Any child presenting with leukocoria must be assumed to have retinoblastoma until proven otherwise because delayed diagnosis may be fatal.<br><br>Prompt fundoscopic examination and imaging are critical for diagnosis and staging. Early treatment can preserve both life and vision.<br><br>Congenital cataract (B) may also cause leukocoria but lacks malignant potential. Persistent pupillary membrane (C) is usually benign.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with choroidal melanoma most commonly develops metastasis to the:",o:["Liver","Brain","Kidney","Lung","Bone marrow"],a:0,e:"The liver is the commonest metastatic site for choroidal melanoma because of hematogenous dissemination through uveal circulation.<br><br>Liver metastasis significantly worsens prognosis and is an important focus during systemic surveillance.<br><br>Brain metastasis (B) is less common initially compared with hepatic spread. Kidney involvement (C) is uncommon.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sebaceous gland carcinoma is most likely to demonstrate which clinical feature?",o:["Madarosis","Bilateral optic atrophy","Cherry-red spot","Relative afferent pupillary defect","Bitemporal hemianopia"],a:0,e:"Loss of eyelashes (madarosis) is an important clue suggesting malignant eyelid disease such as sebaceous gland carcinoma.<br><br>The tumor often masquerades as chronic blepharitis or recurrent chalazion, delaying diagnosis. Diffuse pagetoid spread may occur.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (C) indicates retinal ischemia, while bitemporal hemianopia (E) localizes to optic chiasm lesions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral retinoblastoma most likely has which inheritance pattern?",o:["Autosomal dominant with incomplete penetrance","Autosomal recessive","X-linked dominant","Mitochondrial inheritance","Multifactorial inheritance only"],a:0,e:"Hereditary retinoblastoma follows autosomal dominant inheritance with high penetrance due to germline RB1 mutation. Bilateral disease strongly suggests hereditary transmission.<br><br>Affected individuals require lifelong surveillance for secondary malignancies. Family members may also require genetic counseling.<br><br>X-linked inheritance (C) is not characteristic of retinoblastoma genetics.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A rapidly enlarging vascular retinal tumor associated with von Hippel-Lindau disease is most likely:",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Retinal hemangioblastoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Retinoblastoma","Optic glioma"],a:1,e:"Retinal hemangioblastomas are vascular retinal tumors associated with von Hippel-Lindau syndrome and may cause exudation and retinal detachment.<br><br>Recognition is important because associated systemic lesions include cerebellar hemangioblastomas and renal cell carcinoma.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (D) presents differently with leukocoria and calcification rather than vascular feeder tumors.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ocular melanoma demonstrates acoustic hollowness on ultrasonography. Which tumor is most likely?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Dermoid cyst","Choroidal melanoma","Optic nerve glioma","Conjunctival papilloma"],a:2,e:"Choroidal melanoma characteristically appears as dome-shaped or mushroom-shaped pigmented lesions with acoustic hollowness on ocular ultrasonography.<br><br>Associated findings may include orange pigment and serous retinal detachment. Early detection improves ocular salvage options.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (A) more commonly demonstrates calcification rather than acoustic hollowness.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with AIDS develops a vascular conjunctival tumor caused by HHV-8 infection. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous papilloma","Kaposi sarcoma","Sebaceous carcinoma","Melanocytoma"],a:2,e:"Kaposi sarcoma is a vascular tumor associated with HHV-8 infection and immunosuppression, particularly AIDS.<br><br>Conjunctival lesions appear reddish-purple and may mimic subconjunctival hemorrhage. Systemic evaluation is essential.<br><br>Sebaceous carcinoma (D) causes eyelid thickening rather than vascular conjunctival lesions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic nerve glioma is most commonly associated with which condition?",o:["Tuberous sclerosis","Neurofibromatosis type 1","Sturge-Weber syndrome","Marfan syndrome","Down syndrome"],a:1,e:"Optic nerve gliomas are strongly associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 and often present in childhood with visual loss or proptosis.<br><br>MRI is essential for diagnosis and monitoring. Some tumors remain indolent while others progress significantly.<br><br>Tuberous sclerosis (A) is associated more commonly with retinal astrocytic hamartomas.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with squamous cell carcinoma of conjunctiva most commonly arises at which location?",o:["Superior fornix","Macula","Limbus","Fovea","Optic disc"],a:2,e:"Conjunctival squamous neoplasia commonly develops near the limbus within the interpalpebral fissure, often related to UV exposure.<br><br>Lesions may appear gelatinous, leukoplakic, or papilliform. Excision with cryotherapy is commonly performed.<br><br>Macula (B) and optic disc (E) are retinal structures unrelated to conjunctival surface tumors.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with unilateral proptosis and calcified intraocular mass most likely requires urgent management because the tumor may spread through the:",o:["Canal of Schlemm","Corneal epithelium","Optic nerve","Lens capsule","Zonules only"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma may spread along the optic nerve into the brain, significantly worsening prognosis. Optic nerve invasion is therefore a major pathological concern.<br><br>Early enucleation may be required in advanced disease to prevent extraocular extension and metastatic dissemination.<br><br>Canal of Schlemm (A) and zonules (E) are not major metastatic pathways for retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 5-year-old child with bilateral hereditary retinoblastoma later develops an intracranial pineal region tumor. This condition is known as:",o:["Foster-Kennedy syndrome","Trilateral retinoblastoma","Turcot syndrome","Sturge-Weber syndrome","Li-Fraumeni syndrome"],a:1,e:"Trilateral retinoblastoma refers to bilateral hereditary retinoblastoma associated with an intracranial primitive neuroectodermal tumor, classically in the pineal gland.<br><br>This aggressive association significantly worsens prognosis and highlights the importance of neuroimaging surveillance in hereditary RB1 mutation carriers.<br><br>Foster-Kennedy syndrome (A) involves optic atrophy with contralateral papilledema. Li-Fraumeni syndrome (E) is associated with p53 mutation rather than classic trilateral retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"An elderly patient develops a painless salmon-colored conjunctival lesion in the fornix. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Kaposi sarcoma","Orbital lymphoma","Conjunctival lymphoma","Conjunctival melanoma","Dermolipoma"],a:2,e:"Conjunctival lymphoma classically presents as a painless salmon-pink subepithelial lesion, commonly involving the fornix or bulbar conjunctiva.<br><br>Most lesions are extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphomas. Systemic evaluation is important because ocular disease may represent systemic lymphoma.<br><br>Conjunctival melanoma (D) is pigmented rather than salmon-colored. Dermolipoma (E) is congenital and yellowish rather than lymphoid appearing.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with choroidal melanoma develops mushroom-shaped extension on ultrasonography. This morphology occurs because the tumor has broken through the:",o:["Corneal stroma","Bruch membrane","Optic disc","Lens capsule","Retina only"],a:1,e:"Choroidal melanomas may initially appear dome-shaped but become mushroom-shaped after breaking through Bruch membrane.<br><br>This is a classic imaging description repeatedly tested in ophthalmic oncology recalls. Associated findings include orange pigment and exudative retinal detachment.<br><br>Corneal stroma (A) and lens capsule (D) are unrelated to the morphology of uveal melanoma growth patterns.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent unilateral \"chalazion\" in an elderly patient should always raise suspicion for:",o:["Molluscum contagiosum","Capillary hemangioma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Hordeolum externum","Neurofibroma"],a:2,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma frequently masquerades as recurrent chalazion or chronic unilateral blepharoconjunctivitis, leading to delayed diagnosis.<br><br>Diffuse lid thickening, madarosis, and recurrent disease are important clinical warning signs requiring biopsy.<br><br>Capillary hemangioma (B) occurs mainly in infancy, while hordeolum externum (D) is an acute painful infectious lesion rather than recurrent malignancy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis and downward displacement of the globe most likely has:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Thyroid eye disease","Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Retinoblastoma"],a:2,e:"Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma is the commonest primary malignant orbital tumor of childhood and typically presents with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis.<br><br>The lesion may clinically resemble orbital cellulitis, but imaging reveals an orbital soft tissue mass requiring urgent biopsy and oncologic treatment.<br><br>Dermoid cysts (A) are usually slow-growing congenital lesions. Cavernous hemangioma (D) is more common in adults and progresses slowly.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with conjunctival squamous neoplasia is most strongly associated with which risk factor?",o:["Hypermetropia","Myopia","Ultraviolet exposure","Retinitis pigmentosa","Cataract surgery"],a:2,e:"Conjunctival squamous neoplasia commonly occurs in sun-exposed interpalpebral conjunctiva near the limbus. UV radiation is a major predisposing factor.<br><br>HIV infection and HPV association may also contribute in some patients. Lesions may appear gelatinous or leukoplakic.<br><br>Myopia (B) and hypermetropia (A) have no major role in ocular surface squamous neoplasia development.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with leukocoria and painful red eye develops orbital cellulitis-like appearance secondary to advanced intraocular tumor necrosis. Which tumor is most likely?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Coats disease","Congenital glaucoma","Persistent fetal vasculature","Toxoplasmosis"],a:0,e:"Advanced retinoblastoma may undergo necrosis and inflammation, producing pseudocellulitis or painful secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Leukocoria remains the most important warning sign in pediatric ocular oncology. Delay in diagnosis significantly worsens survival.<br><br>Coats disease (B) may mimic leukocoria but usually lacks aggressive orbital inflammatory extension. Congenital glaucoma (C) produces buphthalmos rather than calcified tumor masses.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with orbital lymphoma most commonly demonstrates which clinical pattern?",o:["Acute painful visual loss","Sudden retinal detachment","Slowly progressive painless proptosis","Episcleritis with hypopyon","Rapid orbital hemorrhage"],a:2,e:"Orbital lymphoma classically presents with slowly progressive painless proptosis and orbital fullness in older adults.<br><br>Imaging often demonstrates molded orbital masses conforming around orbital structures without significant bone destruction. Biopsy confirms diagnosis.<br><br>Acute painful visual loss (A) suggests inflammatory or vascular disease rather than typical lymphoma presentation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic lung carcinoma develops choroidal metastasis because the choroid has abundant:",o:["Lymphatic drainage","Vascular supply","Neural tissue","Melanocytes only","Fibrous septa"],a:1,e:"The choroid possesses one of the richest vascular supplies in the body, making it the commonest ocular site for hematogenous metastasis.<br><br>Breast carcinoma is the commonest source in women, while lung carcinoma predominates in men. Patients often present with blurred vision or serous retinal detachment.<br><br>Lymphatic drainage (A) is limited within the eye and does not explain the frequency of choroidal metastases.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A pigmented choroidal lesion with orange pigment and subretinal fluid is most suspicious for:",o:["Choroidal nevus","Congenital hypertrophy of RPE","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal hemangioma","Coloboma"],a:2,e:"Orange pigment, subretinal fluid, and documented growth are important features suggesting malignant transformation into choroidal melanoma.<br><br>Small benign nevi are common, but suspicious lesions require serial monitoring with ultrasonography and retinal imaging.<br><br>Congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium (B) is typically flat and benign without exudative retinal changes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with optic pathway glioma is most likely to have which associated syndrome?",o:["Marfan syndrome","Down syndrome","Neurofibromatosis type 1","Tuberous sclerosis","Klinefelter syndrome"],a:2,e:"Optic pathway gliomas are strongly associated with NF1 and may involve the optic nerve, chiasm, or optic tracts.<br><br>Children may present with visual decline, proptosis, or precocious puberty if hypothalamic involvement occurs. MRI is the investigation of choice.<br><br>Marfan syndrome (A) is associated with lens subluxation rather than optic glioma. Tuberous sclerosis (D) more commonly causes retinal astrocytic hamartomas.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with eyelid basal cell carcinoma most commonly develops which histological subtype?",o:["Nodular type","Spindle cell type","Pagetoid type","Small round blue cell type","Giant cell type"],a:0,e:"The nodular subtype is the commonest form of basal cell carcinoma and classically presents as a pearly lesion with rolled borders and telangiectasia.<br><br>Ulceration may eventually occur, producing the classic \"rodent ulcer.\" Medial canthal lesions are particularly dangerous because of orbital extension risk.<br><br>Pagetoid spread (C) is more characteristic of sebaceous gland carcinoma than basal cell carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with conjunctival melanoma most commonly arises from:",o:["Retinoblastoma precursor lesion","Dermoid cyst","Primary acquired melanosis","Pinguecula","Capillary hemangioma"],a:2,e:"Conjunctival melanoma frequently develops from primary acquired melanosis with atypia, especially in middle-aged or elderly individuals.<br><br>Growth, feeder vessels, nodularity, and increasing pigmentation are important warning signs requiring excision.<br><br>Pinguecula (D) is a benign degenerative lesion and is not considered a typical precursor of melanoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral retinoblastoma should undergo surveillance imaging mainly to detect:",o:["Choroidal nevus","Orbital cellulitis","Pinealoblastoma","Retinal detachment","Cataract formation"],a:2,e:"Children with hereditary bilateral retinoblastoma are at risk for trilateral retinoblastoma, classically involving pinealoblastoma.<br><br>Regular neuroimaging surveillance is therefore important during early childhood. Prognosis worsens significantly once intracranial extension develops.<br><br>Retinal detachment (D) may occur secondarily but is not the primary reason for surveillance neuroimaging.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with orbital cavernous hemangioma most commonly presents with:",o:["Painful acute proptosis","Leukocoria","Slowly progressive axial proptosis","Sudden visual blackout","Severe conjunctivitis"],a:2,e:"Cavernous hemangioma is the commonest benign orbital tumor in adults and usually presents with slowly progressive painless axial proptosis.<br><br>Imaging typically demonstrates a well-circumscribed intraconal vascular lesion. Surgical excision is considered if symptomatic.<br><br>Painful acute proptosis (A) suggests inflammatory or hemorrhagic conditions rather than cavernous hemangioma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diffuse unilateral conjunctival thickening and pagetoid spread should raise suspicion for:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Choroidal osteoma","Neuroblastoma"],a:2,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma may spread intraepithelially in a pagetoid pattern involving conjunctiva and eyelid epithelium.<br><br>This diffuse spread pattern contributes to delayed diagnosis and poorer prognosis. Multiple map biopsies may be required.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) rarely demonstrates pagetoid conjunctival spread. Retinal astrocytoma (B) is unrelated to conjunctival epithelial disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with leukocoria due to retinoblastoma most commonly demonstrates which examination finding on fundoscopy?",o:["Flat retinal tear","Cherry-red spot","White endophytic retinal mass","Optic disc drusen","Papilledema only"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma commonly appears as a white friable retinal mass projecting into the vitreous cavity with possible vitreous seeding.<br><br>Calcification is frequently present and helps distinguish the lesion radiologically from pseudoretinoblastoma conditions.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (B) is characteristic of central retinal artery occlusion rather than retinal malignancy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ocular surface squamous neoplasia most commonly presents with which lesion morphology?",o:["Gelatinous limbal lesion","Deep choroidal pigmented mass","Intravitreal cyst","Optic nerve edema","Bilateral cataract"],a:0,e:"Ocular surface squamous neoplasia often presents as a gelatinous, papilliform, or leukoplakic lesion near the limbus.<br><br>UV exposure, HIV infection, and HPV association are important risk factors. Histopathological confirmation is essential.<br><br>Choroidal pigmented masses (B) suggest melanoma rather than conjunctival epithelial neoplasia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic choroidal tumor from breast carcinoma most likely develops visual symptoms due to:",o:["Corneal edema","Optic chiasm compression","Exudative retinal detachment","Trabecular obstruction","Vitreous degeneration"],a:2,e:"Choroidal metastases commonly leak fluid beneath the retina, producing serous retinal detachment and progressive blurred vision.<br><br>Patients may complain of metamorphopsia or field defects depending on lesion location. Systemic malignancy history is an important clue.<br><br>Trabecular obstruction (D) causes glaucoma rather than retinal detachment-related visual distortion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with hereditary retinoblastoma undergoes enucleation. Histopathology demonstrating invasion of which structure carries the worst prognosis?",o:["Lens capsule","Optic nerve beyond lamina cribrosa","Corneal epithelium","Vitreous only","Zonules"],a:1,e:"Post-laminar optic nerve invasion indicates increased risk of intracranial extension and metastatic dissemination in retinoblastoma.<br><br>This finding significantly worsens prognosis and often necessitates adjuvant chemotherapy. Histopathological optic nerve assessment is therefore critically important.<br><br>Lens capsule (A) and zonular involvement (E) are far less prognostically significant than optic nerve extension.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with bilateral hereditary retinoblastoma presents with vomiting and signs of raised intracranial pressure. MRI reveals a pineal region mass. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Medulloblastoma","Trilateral retinoblastoma","Optic glioma","Craniopharyngioma","Astrocytoma"],a:1,e:"Trilateral retinoblastoma refers to hereditary bilateral retinoblastoma associated with an intracranial primitive neuroectodermal tumor, most commonly pinealoblastoma.<br><br>This association is repeatedly recalled in FCPS ophthalmology oncology questions because prognosis worsens markedly once intracranial disease develops. MRI surveillance is therefore important in hereditary cases.<br><br>Optic glioma (C) is associated with NF1 rather than RB1 mutation. Craniopharyngioma (D) causes chiasmal compression but is not classically linked to hereditary retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless salmon-pink subconjunctival lesion in an elderly patient is most suggestive of:",o:["Conjunctival melanoma","Squamous papilloma","Pinguecula","Conjunctival lymphoma","Kaposi sarcoma"],a:3,e:"Conjunctival lymphoma classically presents as a painless salmon-colored subepithelial lesion involving bulbar conjunctiva or fornices.<br><br>Most are extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphomas and may represent systemic lymphoproliferative disease. Histopathology and systemic evaluation are essential.<br><br>Conjunctival melanoma (A) is usually pigmented. Pinguecula (C) is yellow-white degenerative tissue rather than lymphoid infiltration.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with conjunctival melanoma demonstrates greatest metastatic risk when the lesion involves the:",o:["Temporal limbus","Corneal epithelium only","Inferior bulbar conjunctiva only","Fornix or caruncle","Tarsal plate only"],a:3,e:"Conjunctival melanomas involving the fornix, caruncle, or orbit demonstrate significantly higher metastatic potential and poorer prognosis.<br><br>Tumor thickness greater than 2 mm and local recurrence are additional adverse prognostic factors. Wide excision using \"no-touch\" technique is recommended.<br><br>Corneal epithelium (B) involvement alone is less prognostically severe compared with deep fornicial or orbital extension.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with slowly progressive painless axial proptosis and well-circumscribed intraconal mass on imaging most likely has:",o:["Orbital cellulitis","Optic nerve glioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Lacrimal gland carcinoma"],a:3,e:"Orbital cavernous hemangioma is the commonest benign orbital tumor in adults and typically presents with slowly progressive painless axial proptosis.<br><br>Imaging reveals a well-defined intraconal vascular lesion. Surgical excision is considered if visual compromise or cosmetic deformity develops.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (A) causes painful inflammatory proptosis, while rhabdomyosarcoma (C) progresses rapidly in children.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent unilateral chronic blepharoconjunctivitis with diffuse conjunctival involvement and madarosis should strongly suggest:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Kaposi sarcoma","Molluscum contagiosum","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Neurofibroma"],a:3,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is notorious for masquerading as recurrent chalazion or unilateral chronic blepharoconjunctivitis. Pagetoid conjunctival spread is characteristic.<br><br>Loss of eyelashes, diffuse thickening, and recurrent unilateral disease are high-yield clues requiring prompt biopsy.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) usually forms nodular pearly lesions rather than diffuse pagetoid conjunctival spread. Molluscum contagiosum (C) causes follicular conjunctivitis rather than malignant infiltration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ocular surface squamous neoplasia most commonly develops lesions near the:",o:["Macula","Peripheral retina","Optic disc","Limbus","Fovea"],a:3,e:"Ocular surface squamous neoplasia typically arises at the limbus within the interpalpebral fissure where ultraviolet exposure is greatest.<br><br>Lesions may appear gelatinous, papilliform, or leukoplakic. Surgical excision with cryotherapy is commonly performed.<br><br>Macula (A) and fovea (E) are retinal structures unrelated to conjunctival epithelial neoplasia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with choroidal melanoma most commonly demonstrates which ultrasonographic feature?",o:["Acoustic shadowing only","Acoustic hollowness","Dense calcification","Hyperreflective vitreous bands","Retinal dialysis"],a:1,e:"Choroidal melanoma classically demonstrates acoustic hollowness on ultrasonography and may appear dome-shaped or mushroom-shaped.<br><br>Associated findings include orange pigment and exudative retinal detachment. Hepatic metastasis remains the major prognostic concern.<br><br>Dense calcification (C) is more typical of retinoblastoma rather than melanoma. Retinal dialysis (E) is unrelated to intraocular tumors.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis and eyelid edema initially treated as orbital cellulitis is later diagnosed with orbital malignancy. Which tumor most likely caused this presentation?",o:["Cavernous hemangioma","Neurofibroma","Dermoid cyst","Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma","Retinoblastoma"],a:3,e:"Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma often mimics orbital cellulitis because of rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis and inflammatory appearance.<br><br>It is the commonest primary malignant orbital tumor of childhood and requires urgent biopsy and oncologic management.<br><br>Dermoid cysts (C) are congenital and slow-growing. Cavernous hemangioma (A) typically presents in adults with gradual painless proptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with primary acquired melanosis of conjunctiva is at greatest risk of developing:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Kaposi sarcoma","Retinoblastoma","Conjunctival melanoma","Squamous papilloma"],a:3,e:"Primary acquired melanosis with atypia is considered a premalignant lesion strongly associated with development of conjunctival melanoma.<br><br>Increasing pigmentation, vascularity, nodularity, and lesion growth warrant biopsy and close surveillance.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) primarily affects eyelid skin rather than conjunctival melanocytic epithelium. Retinoblastoma (C) is a pediatric retinal malignancy unrelated to PAM.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with intraocular lymphoma most commonly presents with:",o:["Leukocoria in infancy","Corneal ulceration","Sudden retinal artery occlusion","Chronic uveitis-like symptoms","Congenital cataract"],a:3,e:"Primary intraocular lymphoma frequently masquerades as chronic steroid-resistant posterior uveitis with floaters and blurred vision.<br><br>Diagnosis is often delayed because symptoms mimic inflammatory disease. Vitreous biopsy may be required for confirmation.<br><br>Leukocoria (A) suggests retinoblastoma. Corneal ulceration (B) is not a typical feature of intraocular lymphoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with conjunctival SCC most commonly spreads first to:",o:["Brain","Regional lymph nodes","Liver","Retina","Choroid"],a:1,e:"Conjunctival squamous cell carcinoma may spread locally or metastasize to regional lymph nodes, especially when diagnosis is delayed.<br><br>Risk factors include UV exposure, HIV infection, and HPV association. Early excision improves prognosis.<br><br>Brain (A) and liver (C) metastases are much less common initial metastatic sites. Retina (D) and choroid (E) are not direct lymphatic drainage targets.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with hereditary retinoblastoma develops osteogenic sarcoma years after successful ocular treatment. This increased risk is related primarily to mutation of:",o:["APC gene","RB1 gene","P53 gene","BRCA2 gene","WT1 gene"],a:1,e:"Germline RB1 mutation predisposes patients to multiple secondary malignancies, especially osteosarcoma, soft tissue sarcomas, and melanoma.<br><br>Radiotherapy further increases this risk in hereditary retinoblastoma survivors. Lifelong surveillance is therefore essential.<br><br>P53 mutation (C) is associated with Li-Fraumeni syndrome rather than classic hereditary retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A pigmented conjunctival lesion showing feeder vessels, nodularity, and recent enlargement should be managed initially with:",o:["Observation only","Laser photocoagulation only","Immediate enucleation","Wide excision biopsy","Topical antibiotics"],a:3,e:"Suspicious conjunctival melanocytic lesions require complete excision using \"no-touch\" technique with cryotherapy to minimize tumor seeding.<br><br>Histopathological assessment determines atypia, invasion, and further management requirements.<br><br>Observation alone (A) risks delayed melanoma diagnosis. Enucleation (C) is reserved for advanced intraocular disease rather than conjunctival lesions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with eyelid basal cell carcinoma most commonly develops which clinical morphology?",o:["Salmon patch lesion","White retinal mass","Diffuse conjunctival thickening","Pearly nodular ulcer","Pigmented choroidal dome"],a:3,e:"Basal cell carcinoma classically presents as a pearly nodular lesion with rolled edges, telangiectasia, and central ulceration.<br><br>The lower eyelid and medial canthus are common sites. Local tissue destruction may be extensive despite rare metastasis.<br><br>Diffuse conjunctival thickening (C) is more characteristic of sebaceous carcinoma with pagetoid spread. White retinal masses (B) occur in retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with orbital lymphoma most commonly belongs to which age group?",o:["Neonates","Young children","Middle-aged to elderly adults","Adolescents only","Premature infants"],a:2,e:"Orbital lymphoma usually presents in older adults with painless progressive proptosis, orbital fullness, or salmon-patch conjunctival lesions.<br><br>Most lesions are non-Hodgkin B-cell lymphomas requiring biopsy and systemic workup. Radiotherapy is commonly effective.<br><br>Young children (B) more commonly develop rhabdomyosarcoma rather than orbital lymphoma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with calcified intraocular tumor and vitreous seeding most likely has:",o:["Coats disease","Toxocariasis","Persistent fetal vasculature","Retinoblastoma","Congenital glaucoma"],a:3,e:"Retinoblastoma frequently demonstrates calcification and vitreous seeding, both highly important diagnostic clues in pediatric ocular oncology.<br><br>Leukocoria and strabismus remain the commonest presenting signs. Management prioritizes life preservation first, then globe and vision salvage.<br><br>Coats disease (A) may mimic leukocoria but usually lacks calcification and true vitreous tumor seeding.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with conjunctival melanoma has greatest recurrence risk when surgery violates which oncologic principle?",o:["Cryotherapy use","Tonometry","Slit-lamp photography","No-touch surgical technique","Refraction testing"],a:3,e:"Conjunctival melanoma surgery emphasizes \"no-touch\" excision to avoid tumor manipulation and seeding of malignant cells.<br><br>Improper surgical handling significantly increases local recurrence risk. Cryotherapy is commonly added to reduce residual disease.<br><br>Tonometry (B) and refraction testing (E) have no direct role in recurrence prevention.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with choroidal metastasis most commonly has primary malignancy arising from:",o:["Thyroid gland","Prostate only","Pancreas","Breast or lung","Skin basal cells"],a:3,e:"Breast carcinoma is the commonest source of choroidal metastasis in women, whereas lung carcinoma predominates in men.<br><br>Patients commonly develop blurred vision from exudative retinal detachment overlying metastatic lesions.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (E) rarely metastasizes hematogenously to the choroid. Pancreatic carcinoma (C) is a much less frequent source.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic nerve glioma associated with NF1 most commonly presents during:",o:["Old age","Late adulthood","Neonatal period only","Childhood","Pregnancy"],a:3,e:"Optic pathway gliomas associated with NF1 usually present in childhood with visual loss, optic atrophy, or proptosis.<br><br>MRI is the investigation of choice, and many tumors remain indolent despite radiological enlargement.<br><br>Late adulthood (B) is more typical for orbital lymphoma or choroidal melanoma rather than optic glioma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Histopathology showing post-laminar optic nerve invasion in retinoblastoma indicates:",o:["Excellent prognosis","Corneal pathology only","Benign disease","Increased metastatic risk","Reduced recurrence risk"],a:3,e:"Post-laminar optic nerve invasion is a major adverse prognostic factor in retinoblastoma because it increases the likelihood of intracranial and systemic spread.<br><br>Such patients often require adjuvant chemotherapy following enucleation. Histopathological optic nerve assessment is therefore critically important.<br><br>Benign disease (C) is incorrect because optic nerve invasion indicates aggressive tumor behavior. Reduced recurrence risk (E) is also incorrect.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 26-year-old man presents with severe ocular pain, circumcorneal congestion, photophobia, and a constricted irregular pupil. Slit-lamp examination reveals cells and flare in the anterior chamber. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Acute conjunctivitis","Retinal detachment","Episcleritis","Acute anterior uveitis","Blepharitis"],a:3,e:"Anterior uveitis classically presents with painful red eye, photophobia, ciliary congestion, and inflammatory cells within the anterior chamber. Posterior synechiae may cause an irregular pupil.<br><br>HLA-B27-associated disease, tuberculosis, sarcoidosis, and autoimmune disorders are important causes repeatedly recalled in FCPS and JCAT exams.<br><br>Conjunctivitis (A) usually causes diffuse redness with discharge but minimal pain or photophobia. Episcleritis (C) is generally mild and self-limiting without anterior chamber reaction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent acute anterior uveitis is most strongly associated with which systemic disease group?",o:["HLA-B27 spondyloarthropathies","Diabetes mellitus","Iron deficiency anemia","Hyperthyroidism","Chronic renal failure"],a:0,e:"HLA-B27-associated disorders such as ankylosing spondylitis, reactive arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, and inflammatory bowel disease are strongly linked to recurrent anterior uveitis.<br><br>These attacks are often unilateral, painful, and recurrent with fibrinous anterior chamber inflammation.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus (B) is associated more with diabetic retinopathy than recurrent nongranulomatous anterior uveitis. Hyperthyroidism (D) primarily affects orbital tissues.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe anterior uveitis develops an irregular fixed pupil due to formation of:",o:["Hypopyon","Posterior synechiae","Keratic precipitates","Band keratopathy","Cyclodialysis cleft"],a:1,e:"Posterior synechiae occur when the inflamed iris adheres to the anterior lens capsule, producing irregular poorly reactive pupils.<br><br>Extensive synechiae may obstruct aqueous flow and precipitate secondary angle-closure glaucoma. Mydriatics help prevent adhesion formation.<br><br>Keratic precipitates (C) are inflammatory endothelial deposits rather than iris-lens adhesions. Hypopyon (A) represents inflammatory cells layered inferiorly in the anterior chamber.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful localized scleral tenderness and violaceous discoloration most likely has:",o:["Episcleritis","Keratoconus","Viral conjunctivitis","Scleritis","Hordeolum"],a:3,e:"Scleritis is a severe painful inflammatory disorder often associated with systemic autoimmune diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis and granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br>Pain is deep, boring, and may radiate to the face or jaw. Necrotizing disease may threaten globe integrity and vision.<br><br>Episcleritis (A) is typically mild, sectoral, and minimally painful. Hordeolum (E) is a localized eyelid infection rather than scleral inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with granulomatous anterior uveitis most classically demonstrates which slit-lamp finding?",o:["Fine dust-like keratic precipitates","Mutton-fat keratic precipitates","Corneal guttata","Dendritic ulcer","Band-shaped opacity"],a:1,e:"Granulomatous uveitis classically produces large greasy \"mutton-fat\" keratic precipitates due to macrophage aggregation on the corneal endothelium.<br><br>Sarcoidosis, tuberculosis, syphilis, and sympathetic ophthalmia are important causes. Iris nodules may also be present.<br><br>Fine keratic precipitates (A) are more typical of nongranulomatous uveitis. Dendritic ulcers (D) suggest herpes simplex keratitis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral red eye, watery discharge, and preauricular lymphadenopathy most likely has:",o:["Bacterial conjunctivitis","Scleritis","Acute glaucoma","Viral conjunctivitis","Uveitis"],a:3,e:"Adenoviral conjunctivitis commonly causes follicular conjunctivitis with watery discharge and tender preauricular lymphadenopathy.<br><br>It is highly contagious and may produce punctate keratitis or subepithelial corneal infiltrates. Strict hygiene is important.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (C) causes severe pain, halos, and raised intraocular pressure rather than follicular conjunctivitis with lymphadenopathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with rheumatoid arthritis develops severe ocular pain and scleral thinning with bluish discoloration. Which ocular pathology is most likely?",o:["Episcleritis","Keratoconjunctivitis sicca","Pinguecula","Necrotizing scleritis","Chalazion"],a:3,e:"Necrotizing scleritis is the most severe form of scleral inflammation and is strongly associated with systemic vasculitic disease, especially rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br>Progressive scleral destruction may lead to perforation and profound visual morbidity if untreated. Systemic immunosuppression is often required.<br><br>Episcleritis (A) is generally benign and non-destructive. Pinguecula (C) is a degenerative conjunctival lesion rather than inflammatory scleral disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Behçet disease most commonly develops which ocular inflammatory manifestation?",o:["Episcleritis only","Retinal detachment only","Isolated blepharitis","Recurrent hypopyon uveitis","Optic nerve glioma"],a:3,e:"Behçet disease classically causes recurrent nongranulomatous uveitis with hypopyon formation and retinal vasculitis.<br><br>The disease may rapidly threaten vision because posterior segment involvement is common and aggressive. Oral and genital ulcers are important systemic clues.<br><br>Blepharitis (C) is not the classic inflammatory ocular lesion of Behçet disease. Optic glioma (E) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with herpes simplex keratitis most classically demonstrates:",o:["Corneal dendritic ulcer","Hypopyon only","Band keratopathy","Cherry-red spot","Macular hole"],a:0,e:"Herpes simplex epithelial keratitis produces branching dendritic ulcers with terminal bulbs that stain with fluorescein.<br><br>Topical steroids may worsen epithelial disease and should be avoided unless stromal involvement is specifically managed.<br><br>Band keratopathy (C) represents calcium deposition and is unrelated to classic HSV epithelial keratitis. Cherry-red spot (D) indicates retinal ischemia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute anterior uveitis develops secondary glaucoma primarily because inflammatory debris obstructs the:",o:["Retina","Corneal stroma","Optic nerve","Trabecular meshwork","Vitreous base"],a:3,e:"Inflammatory cells, fibrin, and proteinaceous material obstruct trabecular outflow during uveitis, producing secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Posterior synechiae causing iris bombe may further worsen pressure elevation by obstructing aqueous flow.<br><br>Retina (A) and vitreous base (E) are unrelated to conventional aqueous drainage pathways.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful nodular scleral inflammation worsened by eye movement most likely has involvement of which tissue?",o:["Conjunctiva only","Lens capsule","Corneal epithelium only","Deep vascular scleral plexus","Vitreous cortex only"],a:3,e:"Scleritis involves deep episcleral and scleral vascular plexuses, explaining the severe pain and violaceous hue.<br><br>Pain often worsens with ocular movement because extraocular muscles insert into the sclera. Systemic autoimmune evaluation is important.<br><br>Conjunctival inflammation alone (A) causes milder discomfort rather than severe deep boring pain.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sarcoidosis develops granulomatous uveitis. Which additional ocular finding is classically associated?",o:["Iris nodules","Retinal dialysis","Macular hole","Coloboma","Keratoconus"],a:0,e:"Sarcoid uveitis commonly demonstrates granulomatous features including mutton-fat keratic precipitates and iris nodules.<br><br>Posterior segment involvement such as periphlebitis and choroidal granulomas may also occur. Chest imaging may reveal hilar lymphadenopathy.<br><br>Keratoconus (E) is a corneal ectatic disorder unrelated to granulomatous uveitis. Retinal dialysis (B) is traumatic retinal pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe photophobia, circumcorneal injection, and consensual pain on shining light into the opposite eye most likely has:",o:["Viral conjunctivitis","Dry eye disease","Episcleritis","Acute anterior uveitis","Blepharitis"],a:3,e:"Consensual photophobia is highly suggestive of anterior uveitis because contraction of the inflamed iris causes pain even when light enters the unaffected eye.<br><br>Slit-lamp examination typically reveals cells, flare, keratic precipitates, and ciliary congestion.<br><br>Viral conjunctivitis (A) causes irritation and watery discharge but not marked consensual photophobia. Dry eye disease (B) causes grittiness rather than deep ocular inflammation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with necrotizing herpetic retinitis most commonly develops inflammation involving which retinal structure?",o:["Peripheral retina","Lens nucleus","Corneal epithelium only","Canal of Schlemm","Optic chiasm"],a:0,e:"Acute retinal necrosis syndrome commonly begins in the peripheral retina with necrotizing retinitis, vasculitis, and vitritis due to herpes virus infection.<br><br>Rapid progression and retinal detachment are major complications requiring urgent antiviral therapy.<br><br>Corneal epithelium (C) involvement occurs in HSV keratitis rather than necrotizing herpetic retinitis. Canal of Schlemm (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with episcleritis most commonly demonstrates which feature?",o:["Severe boring pain","Scleral necrosis","Marked vision loss","Sectoral redness with mild discomfort","Posterior synechiae"],a:3,e:"Episcleritis is a benign superficial inflammatory disorder producing localized redness and mild irritation without significant visual loss.<br><br>Most cases are idiopathic and self-limiting, though some are associated with connective tissue disease.<br><br>Severe pain and scleral necrosis (A, D) suggest scleritis rather than episcleritis. Posterior synechiae (E) occur in uveitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sympathetic ophthalmia most likely develops bilateral granulomatous inflammation after:",o:["Corneal abrasion","Penetrating ocular trauma","Cataract only","Myopia","Dry eye disease"],a:1,e:"Sympathetic ophthalmia is a bilateral granulomatous panuveitis occurring after penetrating injury or intraocular surgery exposing ocular antigens.<br><br>The uninjured \"sympathizing\" eye becomes inflamed due to autoimmune sensitization. Early steroid therapy is vision-saving.<br><br>Simple cataract (C) without penetration does not typically trigger sympathetic ophthalmia. Dry eye disease (E) is unrelated autoimmune surface pathology.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fungal keratitis most characteristically demonstrates:",o:["Feathery corneal infiltrates","Dendritic ulcer","Cherry-red spot","Band keratopathy","Vitreous hemorrhage"],a:0,e:"Fungal keratitis commonly presents with dry elevated corneal infiltrates having feathery margins and satellite lesions.<br><br>Trauma with vegetative matter is an important risk factor, especially in agricultural settings. Delayed diagnosis may result in perforation.<br><br>Dendritic ulcers (B) are typical of herpes simplex epithelial keratitis rather than fungal infection.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with HLA-B27-associated anterior uveitis most commonly develops which type of inflammation?",o:["Chronic painless granulomatous inflammation","Chronic retinal detachment","Isolated posterior segment disease","Viral conjunctivitis only","Acute recurrent nongranulomatous inflammation"],a:4,e:"HLA-B27-associated uveitis classically presents with acute painful recurrent nongranulomatous anterior chamber inflammation.<br><br>Attacks are often unilateral but may alternate between eyes. Fibrin and hypopyon formation may occur in severe cases.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation (A) is more typical of sarcoidosis or tuberculosis. Viral conjunctivitis (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe ocular pain and decreased vision is found to have posterior scleritis. Which investigation is classically helpful?",o:["B-scan ultrasonography","Ishihara testing","Keratometry","Gonioscopy only","Pachymetry"],a:0,e:"Posterior scleritis may demonstrate the classic \"T-sign\" on B-scan ultrasonography due to fluid within Tenon space.<br><br>The disease may mimic orbital or retinal pathology and requires prompt recognition because vision-threatening complications may occur.<br><br>Keratometry (C) evaluates corneal curvature and is unrelated to posterior scleral inflammation. Ishihara testing (B) assesses color vision only.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic untreated anterior uveitis most likely develops which long-term complication?",o:["Cataract formation","Retinal dialysis","Optic nerve glioma","Choroidal osteoma","Coloboma"],a:0,e:"Chronic intraocular inflammation and prolonged corticosteroid therapy both predispose patients with uveitis to complicated cataract formation.<br><br>Secondary glaucoma, cystoid macular edema, band keratopathy, and posterior synechiae are additional important complications.<br><br>Optic nerve glioma (C) and coloboma (E) are unrelated developmental or neoplastic disorders rather than inflammatory sequelae.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 34-year-old man with recurrent unilateral anterior uveitis develops a fixed mid-dilated pupil, shallow anterior chamber, and markedly elevated intraocular pressure. The mechanism of glaucoma is most likely:",o:["Trabecular developmental anomaly","Vitreous hemorrhage","Central retinal vein occlusion","Ciliary body shutdown","Pupillary block with iris bombe"],a:4,e:"Extensive posterior synechiae may produce seclusio pupillae, preventing aqueous passage from posterior to anterior chamber. Pressure accumulation behind the iris causes iris bombe and secondary angle-closure glaucoma.<br><br>This is a classic severe complication of uncontrolled anterior uveitis and requires urgent cycloplegia, corticosteroids, and pressure control. Peripheral iridotomy may be necessary.<br><br>Trabecular anomaly (A) is typical of congenital glaucoma. Ciliary body shutdown (D) usually lowers intraocular pressure rather than causing acute pressure rise.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with granulomatosis with polyangiitis develops severe ocular pain and progressive scleral thinning exposing underlying uveal tissue. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Diffuse episcleritis","Scleromalacia perforans","Necrotizing scleritis with inflammation","Interstitial keratitis","Phlyctenular conjunctivitis"],a:2,e:"Necrotizing scleritis with inflammation is the most destructive form of scleral inflammation and is strongly associated with systemic vasculitic disorders such as granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br>Progressive scleral necrosis may lead to perforation and blindness. Aggressive systemic immunosuppressive therapy is usually required.<br><br>Scleromalacia perforans (B) occurs classically in longstanding rheumatoid arthritis and often progresses with surprisingly little pain or inflammation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis most characteristically demonstrates:",o:["Dense posterior synechiae","Hypopyon formation","Stellate keratic precipitates with heterochromia","Mutton-fat keratic precipitates only","Severe painful attacks"],a:2,e:"Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis is a chronic low-grade anterior uveitis characterized by diffuse stellate keratic precipitates, iris heterochromia, cataract, and secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Unlike most uveitis syndromes, posterior synechiae are uncommon despite chronic inflammation. Patients often have surprisingly mild symptoms.<br><br>Hypopyon (B) is more typical of Behçet disease or severe HLA-B27-associated uveitis. Severe painful attacks (E) are uncommon in Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with AIDS develops retinal necrosis with extensive hemorrhage producing the classic \"pizza pie\" appearance. Which organism is most likely responsible?",o:["Herpes simplex virus","Cytomegalovirus","Candida albicans","Toxoplasma gondii","Varicella zoster virus only"],a:1,e:"CMV retinitis is a major opportunistic ocular infection in immunocompromised patients and classically produces necrotizing hemorrhagic retinitis described as \"pizza pie\" or \"cottage cheese with ketchup.\"<br><br>Untreated disease rapidly progresses along retinal vessels and may lead to retinal detachment and blindness.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (D) produces focal necrotizing retinochoroiditis rather than diffuse hemorrhagic vascular retinal destruction. HSV and VZV typically produce acute retinal necrosis syndrome.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with longstanding rheumatoid arthritis develops painless progressive scleral thinning without marked redness. Which inflammatory disorder is most likely?",o:["Diffuse anterior scleritis","Nodular episcleritis","Scleromalacia perforans","Orbital pseudotumor","Keratouveitis"],a:2,e:"Scleromalacia perforans is a necrotizing scleral disease classically associated with severe longstanding rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br>Unlike typical scleritis, inflammation and pain may be surprisingly minimal despite progressive scleral thinning and exposure of dark uveal tissue.<br><br>Diffuse anterior scleritis (A) is painful and intensely inflamed. Nodular episcleritis (B) is benign and non-destructive.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with toxoplasma retinochoroiditis most classically demonstrates:",o:["Branching dendritic ulcer","\"Headlight in the fog\" appearance","Mutton-fat keratic precipitates","Ring corneal infiltrate","Optic disc drusen"],a:1,e:"Active ocular toxoplasmosis produces focal necrotizing retinitis appearing as a bright white retinal lesion obscured by dense vitritis<br><br>It is the commonest cause of posterior uveitis worldwide and frequently recurs adjacent to old pigmented scars.<br><br>Dendritic ulcers (A) are characteristic of herpes simplex epithelial keratitis. Ring infiltrates (D) suggest Acanthamoeba keratitis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent anterior uveitis develops band-shaped corneal opacity due to calcium deposition in:",o:["Corneal epithelium only","Lens capsule","Descemet membrane only","Endothelium only","Bowman layer and superficial stroma"],a:4,e:"Band keratopathy occurs due to calcium deposition within Bowman layer and superficial corneal stroma, often in chronic uveitis or hypercalcemic states.<br><br>The opacity typically begins in the interpalpebral region and may impair vision if central. EDTA chelation may be required.<br><br>Descemet membrane (C) abnormalities produce guttata rather than band keratopathy. Lens capsule involvement (B) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe ocular pain, restricted eye movements, and diffuse orbital inflammation but no infection most likely has:",o:["Orbital cellulitis","Retinoblastoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Thyroid eye disease only","Orbital pseudotumor"],a:4,e:"Idiopathic orbital inflammatory syndrome (orbital pseudotumor) causes painful orbital inflammation with proptosis, restricted movements, chemosis, and visual compromise.<br><br>Unlike thyroid eye disease, tendon insertions may be involved. Corticosteroids typically produce dramatic improvement.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (A) is infectious and often accompanied by fever and sinus disease. Cavernous hemangioma (C) causes painless gradual proptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic granulomatous uveitis and retinal periphlebitis most likely has underlying:",o:["Sarcoidosis","Migraine","Myopia","Keratoconus","Central serous retinopathy"],a:0,e:"Sarcoidosis frequently causes granulomatous uveitis with retinal periphlebitis producing the classic \"candle-wax drippings\" appearance.<br><br>Pulmonary hilar lymphadenopathy and elevated serum ACE levels may support diagnosis. Posterior segment involvement may significantly threaten vision.<br><br>Myopia (C) and keratoconus (D) are refractive/corneal disorders unrelated to retinal vasculitic inflammation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with herpes zoster ophthalmicus develops sectoral iris atrophy after anterior uveitis. The mechanism is most likely:",o:["Mechanical trauma only","Trabecular dysgenesis","Lens-induced inflammation","Calcium deposition","Ischemic vasculitis of iris vessels"],a:4,e:"Herpes zoster ophthalmicus may cause occlusive vasculitis affecting iris circulation, resulting in characteristic sectoral iris atrophy.<br><br>Associated keratitis, uveitis, elevated intraocular pressure, and cranial nerve palsies may occur. Early antiviral therapy reduces complications.<br><br>Lens-induced inflammation (C) produces phacogenic uveitis rather than sectoral ischemic iris damage.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent bilateral granulomatous panuveitis following penetrating trauma to one eye most likely has:",o:["Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada disease","Sympathetic ophthalmia","Acute retinal necrosis","Behçet disease","Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis"],a:1,e:"Sympathetic ophthalmia is an autoimmune bilateral granulomatous panuveitis triggered by exposure of ocular antigens after penetrating trauma or surgery.<br><br>The sympathizing eye may rapidly lose vision if untreated. Early enucleation of severely damaged eyes may reduce risk.<br><br>VKH disease (A) resembles sympathetic ophthalmia clinically but occurs without trauma and includes integumentary findings.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe corneal pain disproportionate to examination findings and history of contact lens use most likely has:",o:["Bacterial keratitis","Episcleritis","Viral conjunctivitis","Marginal keratitis","Acanthamoeba keratitis"],a:4,e:"Acanthamoeba keratitis classically produces severe pain out of proportion to early clinical signs. Contact lens exposure and contaminated water are major risk factors.<br><br>Ring infiltrates may develop later. Delayed diagnosis is common and can lead to devastating visual loss.<br><br>Bacterial keratitis (A) usually causes more obvious suppurative infiltrates early. Episcleritis (B) is not associated with severe corneal pain.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic anterior uveitis develops cataract primarily because of:",o:["Increased retinal perfusion","Vitreous liquefaction","Corneal endothelial failure only","Excess tear secretion","Persistent inflammation and steroid therapy"],a:4,e:"Both chronic intraocular inflammation and prolonged corticosteroid use contribute significantly to complicated cataract formation in uveitis patients.<br><br>Posterior subcapsular cataracts are especially common. Careful inflammatory control is essential before cataract surgery.<br><br>Retinal perfusion changes (A) and tear secretion (D) are not the primary mechanisms of uveitic cataractogenesis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with tuberculosis-associated uveitis most likely demonstrates which inflammatory pattern?",o:["Purely nongranulomatous conjunctivitis","Congenital cataract","Isolated retinal detachment","Lens subluxation","Granulomatous uveitis"],a:4,e:"Tuberculosis classically produces granulomatous uveitis characterized by mutton-fat keratic precipitates, iris nodules, and chronic inflammation.<br><br>Choroiditis and retinal vasculitis may also occur. Diagnosis often requires systemic evaluation and exclusion of mimicking diseases.<br><br>Lens subluxation (D) is associated more with Marfan syndrome or trauma than granulomatous inflammation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with anterior uveitis develops low intraocular pressure because inflammation suppresses:",o:["Trabecular meshwork","Ciliary body aqueous production","Retinal perfusion","Lens metabolism","Corneal transparency"],a:1,e:"Severe ciliary body inflammation may reduce aqueous humor secretion, producing ocular hypotony during active uveitis.<br><br>Chronic hypotony may eventually cause phthisis bulbi if inflammation remains uncontrolled.<br><br>Trabecular obstruction (A) generally elevates intraocular pressure rather than lowering it. Corneal transparency (E) is not the primary mechanism.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with syphilitic uveitis is most accurately described as:",o:["Always unilateral","Exclusively pediatric","Limited to conjunctiva only","Causing no posterior segment disease","The \"great masquerader\""],a:4,e:"Syphilis is known as the \"great masquerader\" because it can mimic virtually any pattern of ocular inflammation including anterior, intermediate, posterior, or panuveitis.<br><br>Serologic testing should therefore be considered in unexplained ocular inflammatory disease.<br><br>Syphilitic inflammation is often bilateral and may involve posterior segment structures extensively, making options A and D incorrect.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with HLA-B27-associated uveitis develops layering of leukocytes in the anterior chamber. This finding is termed:",o:["Hyphema","Pseudohypopyon","Hyphaema vitrei","Vitritis","Hypopyon"],a:4,e:"Hypopyon refers to layering of inflammatory leukocytes inferiorly within the anterior chamber and may occur in severe anterior uveitis.<br><br>Behçet disease and HLA-B27-associated inflammation are classic causes repeatedly tested in recall MCQs.<br><br>Hyphema (A) refers to blood rather than inflammatory cells. Vitritis (D) involves inflammatory cells within the vitreous cavity.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with orbital cellulitis most commonly develops infection secondary to:",o:["Chronic glaucoma","Cataract surgery only","Retinal detachment","Macular degeneration","Ethmoidal sinusitis"],a:4,e:"Orbital cellulitis most commonly spreads from adjacent ethmoidal sinus infection because of the thin lamina papyracea separating orbit from sinus.<br><br>Painful proptosis, fever, ophthalmoplegia, and reduced vision may occur. Intracranial spread is a serious complication.<br><br>Retinal detachment (C) and macular degeneration (D) are unrelated to orbital infectious spread.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic posterior uveitis develops cystoid macular edema. Vision decreases primarily because of fluid accumulation within the:",o:["Peripheral cornea","Ciliary body only","Optic nerve sheath","Lens cortex","Macular retina"],a:4,e:"Inflammatory breakdown of the blood-retinal barrier causes cystic accumulation of fluid within the macular retina, impairing central vision.<br><br>Cystoid macular edema is among the most important causes of permanent visual loss in chronic uveitis. OCT is highly sensitive for diagnosis.<br><br>Peripheral corneal changes (A) and lens cortex abnormalities (D) do not explain the characteristic central visual distortion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe unilateral granulomatous uveitis, vitiligo, poliosis, and meningismus most likely has:",o:["Behçet disease","Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada syndrome","Sympathetic ophthalmia","CMV retinitis","Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis"],a:1,e:"VKH syndrome is an autoimmune disorder targeting melanocyte-containing tissues and classically causes bilateral granulomatous panuveitis with neurologic and integumentary manifestations.<br><br>Patients may develop vitiligo, poliosis, alopecia, tinnitus, and aseptic meningitis. Early systemic corticosteroid therapy is essential.<br><br>Sympathetic ophthalmia (C) resembles VKH clinically but follows ocular trauma. Behçet disease (A) characteristically causes recurrent hypopyon uveitis rather than integumentary depigmentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 29-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of blurred vision and floaters. Examination reveals vitritis, snowbanking over the pars plana, and cystoid macular edema. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Acute retinal necrosis","Fuchs dystrophy","Anterior scleritis","Viral conjunctivitis","Intermediate uveitis (pars planitis)"],a:4,e:"Intermediate uveitis predominantly involves the vitreous and peripheral retina, especially the pars plana region. Snowballs and snowbanking are classic clinical findings.<br><br>Patients commonly present with floaters and blurred vision due to vitritis or cystoid macular edema. Multiple sclerosis and sarcoidosis are important systemic associations.<br><br>Anterior scleritis (C) causes severe ocular pain rather than vitreous inflammation. Viral conjunctivitis (D) does not produce snowbanking or cystoid macular edema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful red eye and elevated intraocular pressure is diagnosed with herpetic trabeculitis. Which virus most commonly causes this condition?",o:["Adenovirus","Measles virus","Epstein-Barr virus","Cytomegalovirus only in children","Herpes simplex virus"],a:4,e:"HSV-associated anterior uveitis may involve trabecular inflammation causing elevated intraocular pressure disproportionate to anterior chamber activity.<br><br>Sectoral iris atrophy and recurrent unilateral disease are important clinical clues. Antiviral therapy with pressure control is required.<br><br>Adenovirus (A) primarily causes conjunctivitis. Measles virus (B) is associated with keratoconjunctivitis rather than classic herpetic trabeculitis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and severe retinal vasculitis most likely has:",o:["Sarcoidosis","Multiple sclerosis","Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada syndrome","Toxoplasmosis","Behçet disease"],a:4,e:"Behçet disease is a multisystem vasculitic disorder characterized by recurrent oral ulcers, genital ulcers, hypopyon uveitis, and occlusive retinal vasculitis.<br><br>Posterior segment disease is often aggressive and may rapidly threaten vision because of retinal ischemia and macular edema.<br><br>Sarcoidosis (A) more commonly causes granulomatous inflammation and periphlebitis. VKH syndrome (C) is associated with integumentary depigmentation rather than oral-genital ulceration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 38-year-old contact lens wearer presents with severe ocular pain disproportionate to examination findings. Slit lamp later reveals ring-shaped stromal infiltrate. Which organism is most likely responsible?",o:["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Acanthamoeba","Herpes simplex virus","Candida albicans","Staphylococcus epidermidis"],a:1,e:"Acanthamoeba keratitis classically causes severe pain out of proportion to early slit-lamp findings. Ring infiltrates appear later during disease progression.<br><br>Improper contact lens hygiene and contaminated water exposure are major risk factors. Delayed diagnosis frequently results in devastating visual outcomes.<br><br>Pseudomonas (A) causes rapidly suppurative bacterial keratitis with dense infiltrates. HSV (C) classically produces dendritic epithelial ulcers.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with rheumatoid arthritis develops bilateral dry eyes due to autoimmune destruction of the lacrimal glands. Which condition is most likely present?",o:["Keratoconus","Acute retinal necrosis","Episcleritis","Marginal keratitis","Keratoconjunctivitis sicca"],a:4,e:"Keratoconjunctivitis sicca results from deficient aqueous tear production and is strongly associated with autoimmune disease, particularly Sjögren syndrome and rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br>Patients complain of burning, grittiness, fluctuating vision, and photophobia. Chronic disease may cause filamentary keratitis and corneal ulceration.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) is an ectatic corneal disorder unrelated to lacrimal gland autoimmunity. Acute retinal necrosis (B) is infectious posterior segment inflammation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe fungal keratitis most characteristically develops:",o:["Branching dendrites","Satellite lesions with feathery infiltrates","Cherry-red spot","Optic disc edema","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Fungal keratitis commonly demonstrates dry-looking infiltrates with feathery margins and surrounding satellite lesions.<br><br>Trauma with vegetative matter is a classic risk factor in agricultural workers. Delay in treatment may result in perforation and endophthalmitis.<br><br>Branching dendrites (A) are characteristic of HSV epithelial keratitis. Cherry-red spot (C) indicates retinal ischemia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with anterior uveitis develops perilimbal vascular congestion known as:",o:["Subconjunctival hemorrhage","Papilledema","Pinguecula","Arcus senilis","Ciliary flush"],a:4,e:"Ciliary flush refers to circumcorneal injection produced by dilation of deep episcleral and ciliary vessels in anterior segment inflammation.<br><br>It is an important sign in anterior uveitis, keratitis, and acute glaucoma. The redness is concentrated around the limbus.<br><br>Subconjunctival hemorrhage (A) produces sharply demarcated painless bleeding without perilimbal vascular congestion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with posterior uveitis develops retinal vasculitis and branch retinal artery occlusion. Which inflammatory disease is classically associated?",o:["Behçet disease","Chalazion","Episcleritis","Fuchs dystrophy","Hordeolum internum"],a:0,e:"Behçet disease may produce severe occlusive retinal vasculitis involving both arteries and veins, leading to ischemia and visual loss.<br><br>The disease is notorious for recurrent inflammatory attacks and poor visual prognosis without aggressive immunosuppressive therapy.<br><br>Episcleritis (C) is superficial and non-occlusive. Hordeolum (E) is an eyelid infection unrelated to retinal vascular inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old patient presents with bilateral granulomatous panuveitis, exudative retinal detachments, tinnitus, alopecia, and vitiligo. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Sympathetic ophthalmia","Behçet disease","Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada syndrome","CMV retinitis","Toxoplasmosis"],a:2,e:"VKH syndrome is an autoimmune disorder targeting melanocyte-containing tissues and classically causes bilateral granulomatous panuveitis with neurologic and integumentary findings.<br><br>Serous retinal detachments, tinnitus, vitiligo, and poliosis are highly characteristic. Early systemic corticosteroid therapy is essential.<br><br>Sympathetic ophthalmia (A) resembles VKH clinically but follows penetrating ocular trauma. CMV retinitis (D) occurs mainly in immunocompromised patients.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent unilateral hypertensive anterior uveitis and diffuse stellate keratic precipitates most likely has:",o:["Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Marginal keratitis","Episcleritis","Central retinal vein occlusion"],a:0,e:"Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis causes chronic low-grade inflammation with diffuse stellate keratic precipitates and frequently secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Patients often have heterochromia and cataract but surprisingly mild symptoms despite chronic disease. Posterior synechiae are uncommon.<br><br>Acute angle closure glaucoma (B) causes severe pain and corneal edema rather than chronic mild inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with syphilitic posterior uveitis is best described by which phrase commonly used in ophthalmology?",o:["The silent destroyer","The dry eye disorder","The red reflex disease","The painful eye syndrome","The great masquerader"],a:4,e:"Syphilis is known as the \"great masquerader\" because it can imitate virtually any form of ocular inflammatory disease.<br><br>It may present as anterior, posterior, intermediate, or panuveitis with highly variable clinical findings. Serologic testing is essential in unexplained uveitis.<br><br>The disease is not limited to painful or dry eye syndromes, making options D and E incorrect.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with orbital cellulitis develops reduced vision and ophthalmoplegia. Which adjacent anatomical structure most commonly serves as the infection source?",o:["Maxillary sinus only","Retina","Frontal cortex","Lacrimal gland only","Ethmoid sinus"],a:4,e:"Orbital cellulitis most commonly spreads from ethmoid sinusitis because the thin lamina papyracea provides minimal barrier between orbit and sinus.<br><br>Painful proptosis, ophthalmoplegia, decreased vision, and fever are important clinical signs. Intracranial spread may occur.<br><br>Retina (B) is not a source of orbital infection. Lacrimal gland disease (D) causes dacryoadenitis rather than typical cellulitis spread.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic uveitis develops dense calcific deposition in the interpalpebral cornea. Which complication is this?",o:["Keratoglobus","Arcus juvenilis","Corneal hydrops","Keratomalacia","Band keratopathy"],a:4,e:"Band keratopathy results from calcium deposition in Bowman layer and superficial corneal stroma, commonly in chronic inflammatory ocular disease.<br><br>The opacity begins in the interpalpebral area and may impair central vision if progressive. EDTA chelation therapy may be required.<br><br>Keratoglobus (A) is a corneal ectatic disorder rather than calcific degeneration. Corneal hydrops (C) occurs in keratoconus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe posterior scleritis demonstrates retinal folds, choroidal effusion, and the classic \"T-sign\" on ultrasonography. Which pathology explains the sign?",o:["Vitreous hemorrhage","Corneal edema","Retinal calcification","Optic nerve glioma","Fluid in Tenon space"],a:4,e:"The \"T-sign\" on B-scan ultrasonography results from fluid accumulation within Tenon space adjacent to the optic nerve shadow in posterior scleritis.<br><br>Posterior scleritis may mimic orbital tumors or retinal disease and often presents with severe pain and decreased vision.<br><br>Retinal calcification (C) suggests retinoblastoma rather than posterior scleral inflammation. Corneal edema (B) does not create the T-sign.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with endogenous endophthalmitis most commonly develops ocular infection through:",o:["Direct corneal trauma only","Autoimmune inflammation","Retinal dialysis","Contact lens wear only","Hematogenous spread"],a:4,e:"Endogenous endophthalmitis results from hematogenous dissemination of infectious organisms into intraocular tissues from systemic infection.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus, intravenous drug use, septicemia, and immunocompromised states are major risk factors. Visual prognosis is often poor.<br><br>Direct trauma (A) is responsible for exogenous rather than endogenous endophthalmitis. Autoimmune inflammation (B) does not cause infective endophthalmitis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CMV retinitis most commonly develops retinal detachment because of:",o:["Progressive retinal necrosis","Lens-induced inflammation","Corneal perforation","Optic nerve edema only","Trabecular fibrosis"],a:0,e:"CMV retinitis causes full-thickness retinal necrosis that weakens retinal architecture and predisposes to retinal tears and detachment.<br><br>Retinal detachment is a major cause of severe visual loss in advanced CMV disease despite antiviral treatment.<br><br>Lens inflammation (B) and trabecular fibrosis (E) are not the primary mechanisms for CMV-related retinal detachment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute anterior uveitis demonstrates inflammatory protein leakage into the aqueous humor visible as light scattering on slit lamp. This finding is called:",o:["Flare","Hypopyon","Seclusio pupillae","Keratic precipitation","Iris bombe"],a:0,e:"Aqueous flare occurs due to protein leakage from inflamed iris and ciliary body vessels into the anterior chamber.<br><br>On slit lamp examination it appears as a smoky beam caused by light scattering through protein-rich aqueous humor.<br><br>Hypopyon (B) refers specifically to layering leukocytes. Keratic precipitates (D) are endothelial inflammatory deposits rather than suspended protein.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe necrotizing scleritis is at greatest risk of developing:",o:["Corneal astigmatism only","Arcus senilis","Pinguecula","Retinal migraine","Globe perforation"],a:4,e:"Necrotizing scleritis progressively destroys scleral tissue and may ultimately lead to perforation and irreversible visual loss.<br><br>Aggressive systemic immunosuppressive therapy is often required because topical therapy alone is inadequate.<br><br>Pinguecula (C) and arcus senilis (B) are benign degenerative conditions unrelated to destructive scleral inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent posterior uveitis develops decreased central vision due to cystoid macular edema. Which investigation is most sensitive for detecting this complication?",o:["Gonioscopy","Pachymetry","Keratometry","Schirmer testing","Optical coherence tomography"],a:4,e:"OCT provides highly sensitive cross-sectional imaging demonstrating intraretinal cystic spaces and retinal thickening in cystoid macular edema.<br><br>It is essential for monitoring inflammatory macular disease and response to therapy.<br><br>Gonioscopy (A) evaluates the anterior chamber angle and does not detect macular edema. Schirmer testing (D) evaluates tear production.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent granulomatous anterior uveitis demonstrates Busacca nodules. These nodules are located on the:",o:["Pupillary margin only","Iris surface away from the pupil","Corneal endothelium","Lens capsule","Trabecular meshwork"],a:1,e:"Busacca nodules are granulomatous inflammatory nodules located on the iris surface away from the pupillary margin.<br><br>Koeppe nodules, in contrast, occur at the pupillary border. Both are associated with granulomatous uveitis such as sarcoidosis or tuberculosis.<br><br>Corneal endothelium (C) contains keratic precipitates rather than Busacca nodules. Trabecular meshwork (E) is not the location of iris nodules.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
];